    "body": "Hi @tillkolter. This is an interesting issue. Thanks for opening and apologies for the delay in responding. (There's more on this topic in the [advanced features section](http://truffleframework.com/docs/getting_started/solidity-tests#advanced-features) of the Solidity testing docs.) \r\n\r\nTruffle does some magic behind the scenes of the Solidity tests to make ether available in the Test contracts. If you declare a `uint public initialBalance` at the top of any test, you'll be able to fund other contracts and send eth around as shown below. \r\n\r\nYour specific question related to funding a contract on creation and that case is covered last in this example - but have included some other `send` cases for clarity.\r\n\r\nIf we have a `Payable` contract:\r\n```javascript\r\ncontract Payable {\r\n    \r\n    // Constructor which allows us to fund contract on creation\r\n    function Payable() public payable {\r\n    }\r\n    \r\n    // `fallback` function called when eth is sent to Payable contract\r\n    function () payable {\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\nWe can write the following test:\r\n```javascript\r\npragma solidity ^0.4.18;\r\n\r\nimport \"truffle/Assert.sol\";\r\nimport \"truffle/DeployedAddresses.sol\";\r\nimport \"../contracts/Payable.sol\";\r\n\r\ncontract TestMetacoin {\r\n  \r\n  // Truffle looks for `initialBalance` when it compiles the test suite \r\n  // and funds this test contract with the specified amount on deployment.\r\n  uint public initialBalance = 10 ether;\r\n\r\n  function testSendingEther() public {\r\n    \r\n    // The `this` contract (e.g. TestMetacoin) should have a \r\n    // starting balance of 10 ether \r\n    Assert.equal(this.balance, 10 ether);\r\n  \r\n    // A new Payable contract has a zero balance\r\n    address pay = new Payable();\r\n    Assert.equal(pay.balance, 0);\r\n    \r\n    // Send `pay` 5000 wei (it's being sent by `TestMetacoin`).  Wei is the default\r\n    // denomination in Solidity if you don't specify another unit \r\n    pay.send(5000); \r\n    Assert.equal(pay.balance, 5000 wei);\r\n\r\n    // We can also fund a contract on creation. Solidity's syntax for this is a \r\n    // little unusual :) If the `Payable` contract's constructor took arguments, \r\n    // they would go in the final parentheses attached to the new expression.\r\n    address anotherPay = (new Payable).value(1 ether)(); \r\n    Assert.equal(anotherPay.balance, 1 ether);\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nClosing for house-keeping because Truffle's solidity-testing ether mechanism appears to be working correctly. Thanks again for raising this question.",
